Thousands of the two most notable religious Faith’s and adherents of Islamic and Christian faiths both observed  their Friday and  Sunday prayers behind closed doors in compliance with  the lock down order imposed by Governor Abdullahi Umar Ganduje for the past three days across the state . An investigation conducted by LEADERSHIP in the state Capital revealed that across the Metropolis revealed that Worshippers, in adherence to the stay-at-home order, did not go to their places of worship as it used to be with the Muslim Ummah on Fridays and Christians on Sundays. Speaking to journalists, the chairman of the Council of Ulama in the state Sheikh Ibrahim Khalil and that of the Christian Association of Nigeria (CAN) Kano State Chapter, Reverend Adeyemo Samuel, said all Islamic and Christian spiritual leaders were directed to order their followers to comply with the stay-at-home order. Stating further that circulars and reminder notices were dispatched to all Mosque and Churches mandating them to adhere to the order issued by the state government. They noted that though millions of adherents of the two notable Faiths could not attend Fridays and Sunday worship, on the basis that “only the living can serve God.” “You cannot serve God in the grave,” he stated, adding that men of God are expected to exercise Medical precautions in the fight against what he described as threat to humanity posed by the COVID 19 Pandemic. According to them the two faiths were confronted with challenges of enforcing the lock down order, explaining that there were those who didn’t believe COVID-19 exist. “We had to educate and sensitize our people to comprehend the dangers confronting mankind at this time. It is unprecedented.     